replies.body:
Concerning Press the Attack, I just think the 3 auto proc condition and the chunk of damage up front make it too similar to electrocute but more restrictive. Like, electrocute can be 3 autos or 3 abilities or whatever mix, for one thing, making it easier to apply. And if electrocute does significantly higher damage then I wonder if the bonus damage taken will exceed the difference in proc damage in many cases. It might be better on champions that aren't building damage, but I don't know why a tank would want precision much anyway (though a tank keystone in the tree could be the whole point for all I know) and for a damage dealer it seems as someone who has not played with it to be inferior to most alternatives.  I'm sure some people will like it and I don't hate it, I just am not sure I would get any use out of it.

For Dark Harvest, the increased buff duration after 100 stacks is the change that made it look awesome to me. I think it will be really fun on reset champs, whereas in the earlier version it seemed unsafe vs electrocute because it was awkward to enter a fight with the buff so you couldn't burst a person to get your resets going.
{{sticker:katarina-love}} 

For Guardian, the change to proccing off proximity or ally-targeted skills as well as the addition of the haste are great. I look forward to playing with this on Braum and maybe even Thresh. When it was right click application only and you had a (reduced) cooldown even if it did not proc (which I gather from current tooltip is no longer the case) it seemed too pattern warping to use. Now that it isn't annoying it looks awesome. I might even take on some enchanters if I am not feeling Airie at the time.

For Arcane Comet the addition of cooldown reduction on successive ability damage changes it completely. I hated (and am still not thrilled about) the unreliability of the damage, but now that the cooldown is going to be lower in nearly all cases it is less punishing to miss. Also, if I am reading correctly, dot champions like malzahar and machine gun champions like ryze can get a noticeable dps increase out of it now instead of just an occusional puff of frustrated wishes.
{{sticker:slayer-jinx-wink}} 

For Zombie Ward it was the addition of your own wards returning as zombies as well. I love vision, but I am more excited by getting more out of my own placed wards than the previous soul purpose of gaining an advantage from the hopefully-usefully-placed-yet-detectable wards of my enemies.

For eyeball collection this might sound mean but I am just happy it was changed twice, and in my opinion both changes were nerfs. The first iteration was uncapped which annoyed me since between that and gathering storm I expected every single damage oriented champ to have absurd late-game damage even against tanks, which I was afraid would make all melee champs (without untargetability/stealth) required to get the the hp scaling options in resolve in order to survive. The next version was capped thankfully, but it offered pen at full stacks which seemed too good to pass up. Now that it is capped and only AD or AP it can be balanced against absolute focus or waterwalking and also lets me feel that taking zombie ward or ghost poro is an option.

Sudden impact I am happy about the current version of because I play a lot of Annie in rotating game modes and ARAM. Moar painful flash-Tibbers = a merrier me {{sticker:sg-syndra}} 

I am a little worried that the inspiration keystones (all of them) might be too good in higher level play and get nerfed down till goldies like myself can't make real use of them, but for now they look really neat too.

Anyway, I check surrender at 20 and the forums every single day to see all the changes.  I am just that excited!

{{sticker:vlad-salute}}
